q8.final_answer_text:
Cool roofs are faster as a heat intervention, while tree canopy provides broader public-realm benefits.

Cool roofs are described as "fastest on flat commercial roofs, schools, warehouses, and public buildings where procurement can be centralized," and are "faster and easier to target building by building," capable of reducing building cooling load quickly.

In contrast, tree planting "is slower" and adds benefits "over a longer time horizon." However, tree canopy offers broader public-realm benefits: "trees add shade, stormwater capture, and public-realm comfort." Trees are also "co-beneficial," contributing to "shade, biodiversity, groundwater recharge, and cooler microclimates." The evidence highlights that neighborhoods with "less tree canopy" often face "higher outdoor temperatures," underscoring the public-realm benefit of tree planting in mitigating this. While cool roofs offer benefits like "lower indoor temperatures, lower air-conditioning demand, and reduced peak electricity load during heat waves," which are primarily building-centric, poorly specified reflective roofs "can create glare," which could have a negative public-realm impact.

