q10.final_answer_text:
This Kasten does not mention Jane Jacobs.

Cool roofs, however, are discussed as a strategy to mitigate urban heat. They are defined as using high solar reflectance and thermal emittance materials, which enables buildings to absorb less heat. The benefits of cool roofs include lower indoor temperatures, reduced air-conditioning demand, and a decrease in peak electricity load during heat waves. The zettel notes that cool roofs can quickly reduce building cooling load.

Regarding their implementation, cool roofs are considered fastest to deploy on flat commercial roofs, schools, warehouses, and public buildings where procurement can be centralized. However, their effectiveness is context-dependent: they are most valuable in hot, sunny climates, require pairing with insulation and ventilation in older buildings, and can create glare if poorly specified.

Cool roofs are positioned as one component within a broader "mitigation stack" for urban heat islands, alongside shade trees, reflective pavements, shaded transit stops, cooling centers, and heat-alert outreach. When contrasted with tree canopy, cool roofs are described as faster and easier to target building by building, offering a quick reduction in cooling load. In comparison, trees provide additional benefits like shade, stormwater capture, and public-realm comfort, but over a longer time horizon and with slower implementation. Dark roofs are identified as a contributing factor to the formation of urban heat islands, which keep dense neighborhoods 5 to 10 degrees Fahrenheit warmer.

